"The first workshop took place in the rural teacher-training college Raúl Isidro Burgos in Ayotzinapa before the first tribunal hearing in Guerrero. Other three workshops were held in Chilpancingo, with the remaining tribunals hearings being conducted here. One of the main learning experiences for us was to be flexible to adapt and change the curriculum of the workshops according to modifications in the agenda, such as the number of participants, time limitations, conditions of spaces, etc. After each class, the somatic team evaluated the session and planned necessary curve modifications for the next day. The first session in Ayotzinapa lasted 30 minutes and was repeated twice with different participants arriving at various times. The goal was to foster a sense of arrival and connection among participants who had traveled for many hours. We guided playful dynamics like simple breathing and movement patterns, as well as activities involving passing a hulahoop, to create collaborative learning. The sessions in Chilpancingo were held after the tribunals hearing times, offering one and a half-hour sessions adjusted to delays and changes. Between 7 to 11 participants attended each session. Some participants attended all three sessions in Chilpancingo while others attended only one. Therefore, we created independent sessions that followed almost the same curriculum with small variations. A few participants had already experienced corporeal practices which was particularly helpful for those with less experience and felt it as a way to establish body-level connections. Most of the participants were adults, including a mix of genders. Those who shared their cases during hearings also participated in tribunals hearing sessions. Others were ITCPM staff members overseeing logistics or artists, community activists, lawyers, and national and international judges. Generating a connection at the body level helped reduce attention to differences in education, profession, gender, roles, etc. A female judge said she felt closer to others during the session, indicating a body-level connection without words for other participants who had shared cases in hearings. Another participant mentioned feeling calmer now after the hearing. For another male participant who gave testimony, the testimony was helpful but ":["we made collective actions and dedicated time to each of us."

"The Parallels series explores the intersections of Black American dance with mainstream modern dance, examining the evolution and challenges faced by Black choreographers. In 1982, Ishmael Houston-Jones, Ralph Lemon, Bebe Miller, and others were curating a program at St. Mark's Church in Danspace, featuring works that were considered to be outside the mainstream dance forms of post-Modern times. The series highlights how Black choreographers have contributed to a new generation of dance-making, blending experimental elements with traditional dance influences while challenging the conventions set by mainstream dance movements. The performances also reflect a deep personal connection between performers and audience members, creating a dynamic and integrative experience that transcends mere technical skills.":"Ishmael Houston-Jones was part of the original 1982 Parallels series at Danspace Project in St. Mark's Church, which included Bebe Miller and others. The series explores how Black choreographers have evolved into a new generation disrupting mainstream dance, using experimental forms while maintaining a connection to their cultural roots. The performances reflect a blend of traditional and modern elements, challenging conventions but deeply personalizing the experience with audience interaction."}
